1. Transition to Remote Execution (The "No-RDP" Goal)
Instead of RDPing into the EC2s, you should be able to trigger your scripts from a centralized machine (or a CI/CD runner) using WinRM or SSM Run Command.

AWS Systems Manager (SSM) Run Command: This is your best friend for EC2s. It allows you to execute PowerShell or Python scripts on your EC2 instances without needing an active RDP session. You can send commands via the AWS CLI, effectively automating your "pull and execute" process from a central hub.

3. Shift from "Script Execution" to "Automated Deployment"
Create a simple runner (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, or even a Jenkins node) that connects to your AWS environment.

The Pipeline: 1.  Push code to GitHub.
2.  CI/CD runner triggers an AWS SSM command.
3.  The EC2 instance pulls the code and executes.
4.  The runner monitors the service status via the ArcGIS Server Administrator API to ensure everything is "Healthy" after the update.

*** My advice for your next step: Stop the manual RDP sessions. Start by moving one repeatable task (e.g., updating a Python utility script) to an AWS SSM Run Command. Once you see that you can execute that without RDP, you will see the path to automating the rest of your deployment cycle.

Your current workflow—"Manual RDP + Pull + Execute"—is the industry-standard "Traditional Enterprise" approach for GIS. You are not alone in this; a massive percentage of GIS shops operate exactly this way.

You are correct that the complexity of the environments is a huge factor, but the real reason for this "Manual Gap" is that ArcGIS Enterprise is stateful and tightly coupled. In a standard web app, you deploy a container, and the environment is essentially disposable. In ArcGIS, you are not just deploying code; you are often performing surgery on a live, highly-sensitive production data engine.

1. Stateful: "The System Remembers"
A stateful system is one that remembers previous interactions and stores data that persists over time. In ArcGIS Enterprise, the system is "stateful" at almost every layer.

2. Tightly Coupled: "Everything is Interconnected"
A tightly coupled system means the various components (Portal, Server, Data Store, Web Adaptor) are so heavily dependent on each other that they act like a single, monolithic machine rather than independent parts.